Description: If in the household there is a person over age 55 and a person over age 25, and there is at least 18 years difference between them, then turn on Senior in Household.
Source/Point of Collection: This element is inferred from the ages of the people that have been householded together.

Description: Indicates the age of the person in one-year increments.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Description: Indicates the age of the person.  Age range is expressed in two-year increments.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Attribute Name: Age - Person Default to 1st Person in Household
Description:
Indicates the age of the person. Age range is expressed in two-year increments. 
This element contains 2 fields, an age and a precision level.
If the age of the person is missing, the 1st person's age will be filled in. The 1st person is determined by InfoBase using a series of rules. To distinguish between the age of the person and the 1st person in the household, a match indicator (8627_02) is provided.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Attribute Name: Age - Person Default to 1st Person in Household - Precision Level
Description: Indicates the precision of the data appended: Person or 1st Person.
Value Encodings: I = Input Name Match|F = Default to 1st Individual

Attribute Name: Age in Two-Year Increments - 1st Person in Household
Description:
Indicates the age of the person ranked 1st in the household, based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
NOTE: Age data is calculated from date of birth.  The age calculated may be based on complete date of birth (year, month and day) or incomplete date of birth (year and month or year-only).  If date of birth is not populated, age elements will not be populated.  The exception to this is modeled/inferred age data, which is only in the PLUS and 100% elements, and is indicated as modeled or inferred.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Attribute Name: Age in Two-Year Increments - 1st Person in Household - Plus
Description:
Indicates the age of the person ranked 1st in the household, based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  Includes inferred/modeled data.
Based on 8616 Age in Two-Year Increments-1st Person in the Household, this 9616 Age in Two-Year Increments-1st Person in the Household includes inferred/modeled data to increase the coverage up to the household level match rate.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported data and Acxiom modeled data

Attribute Name: Age in Two-Year Increments - 1st Person in Household - 100%
Description:
Indicates the age of the person ranked 1st in the household, based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  Includes inferred/modeled data and data calculated on the mode of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.
Based on 9616 Age in Two-Year Increments-1st Person in the Household PLUS, this 7616 Age in Two-Year Increments-1st Person in the Household includes data calculated on the mode of the ZIP+4 and ZIP to increase the coverage up to the 100%.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported data, Acxiom modeled data, ZIP+4, and ZIP data

Attribute Name: Age in Two-Year Increments - 1st Person in Household - 100% - Precision Level
Description: Indicates the precision of the data appended: Household, Household Inferred, ZIP+4 or ZIP

Attribute Name: Geoscape - Hispanic Dominant Country of Origin
Description: Identifies the predominant Hispanic country of origin. Predominant origin variables identify the primary country of origin within each geography. Based on country of origin scores and neighborhood characteristics to select the most dominant country of origin for each geography.
Valid Values: AR, BO, CL, CO, CR, CU, DO, EC, GT, HN, MIX, MX, NI, PA, PE, PR, PY, SV, UY, VE
Value Encodings: AR = Argentina, BO = Bolivia, CL = Chile, CO = Colombia, CR = Costa Rica, CU = Cuba, DO = Dominican Republic, EC = Ecuador, GT = Guatemala, HN = Honduras, MIX = Mixed-indicated area where no single race or ethnic group is dominant, MX = Mexico, NI = Nicaragua, PA = Panama, PE = Peru, PR = Puerto Rico, PY = Paraguay, SV = El Salvador, UY = Uruguay, VE = Venezuela
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Description:
Indicates that someone in the household has had a baby in the last 12 months. When 12 months is reached, the element goes to blank.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Those ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have a much reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.  This particular element may have 0 coverage in California.
Value Encodings: A = New Parent in the household - 6 Months or Less|B = New Parent in the household - 7, 8 or 9 Months|C = New Parent in the household - 10, 11 or 12 Months
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have a much reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported data, Acxiom modeled data, ZIP+4, and ZIP data

Attribute Name: Date of Birth - 5th Person in Household (YYYY/MM/DD)
Description:
Indicates the Year, Month and Day of Birth associated with the 5th ranked person in the household.  The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Acxiom policy allows full DOB to be provided to clients for legitimate reference purposes and applications.  Providing DOB to support client marketing applications is not a standard practice due to the sensitive nature of the data, industry and consumer concerns regarding its potential misuse.  However, exceptions to this policy will be considered by Acxiom Management and Privacy Teams where a significant need for full DOB is demonstrated and where privacy and consumer sensitivities are addressed in the subsequent marketing use of the data.  Contact PIAUseCase@acxiom.com if complete DOB is needed.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|DD fields.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported
Restrictions: R4 - All use cases require a PIA

Description:
Indicates the known number of children in the household.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.
Value Encodings: 0 = No children|1 = 1 Child|2 = 2 Children|3 = 3 Children|4 = 4 Children|5 = 5 Children|6 = 6 Children|7 = 7 Children|8 = Greater than 7 Children
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported from registrations to receive product or service promotion offers, from sites or applications that offer information, convenience, discounts and coupons in exchange for completed surveys, from sites that provide information based on college and career interests, and general questionairres.

Description:
Indicates the number of children in the household.  Includes modeled/inferred data added to the value of '0 Number of Children' to extend the coverage to the household level.
This 9602 Number of Children includes a household inferred model that brings the coverage up to the household level match rate.  The basis of this element is 8602 Number of Children.  Since the coverage of 8602 Number of Children 'greater than 0' is already near the census percentage, household inferred/modeled data is only added to '0 Number of Children'.
NOTE: For the HOUSEHOLD LEVEL children's data: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.
Value Encodings: 0 = No children|1 = 1 Child|2 = 2 Children|3 = 3 Children|4 = 4 Children|5 = 5 Children|6 = 6 Children|7 = 7 Children|8 = Greater than 7 Children
Source/Point of Collection:
Number of Children is both source provided and inferred from all the self-reported data evaluated.

Description:

This 7602 Number of Children includes a calculated mode of Number of Children from the ZIP9 and ZIP which brings the coverage up to 100%.  The basis of this element is 9602 Number of Children PLUS.  Calculating the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP can add data to all Number of Children values.
NOTE: For the HOUSEHOLD LEVEL children's data: The children's names are not provided by the sources. Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.
Value Encodings: 0 = No children|1 = 1 Child|2 = 2 Children|3 = 3 Children|4 = 4 Children|5 = 5 Children|6 = 6 Children|7 = 7 Children|8 = Greater than 7 Children
Source/Point of Collection:
Number of Children is both source provided and inferred from all the self-reported data evaluated.

Attribute Name: Probable New Teen Driver - Age Indicator
Description: The element predicts the household has a teenager who will start driving within months or has just started driving. The primary function of the element is to help auto insurance marketers identify new prospects at a time when consumers shop for insurance. This element considers the legal driving age in each state and provides information whether the teenager has reached the legal driving age or not.
Value Encodings: A = Within 1 year until full drivers license age|B = Reached Full Drivers License Age
Source/Point of Collection: Inferred from age data and U.S. state information regarding the youngest age for driving permits or licenses.

The primary function of the element is to help auto insurance marketers identify new prospects at a time when consumers shop for insurance. The element provides the gender of the teenager.

Source/Point of Collection: Inferred from age data and U.S. state information regarding the youngest age for driving permits or licenses.

Description:
The CPI score is a representation of the amount of individual data available per consumer.  The score illuminates depth of data available for a person, and provides an easy-to-use relative measure of how active a person is in the marketplace.
The CPI rules are proprietary, but in general a set of business rules is used to calculate this element.  A count is generated from the number of frequently updated sources for some of the person-level data, and then that count is pushed into buckets of 01-10.
Value Encodings: 00 = Match No Record Content|01 = Smallest Marketing Footprint|02|03|04|05|06|07|08|09|10 = Largest Marketing Footprint
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules review the person-scoped elements and their contributing sources to provide this indicator.

Description:
The CPI score is a representation of the amount of individual data available per consumer.  The score illuminates depth of data available for a person, and provides an easy-to-use relative measure of how active a person is in the marketplace.
The CPI rules are proprietary, but in general a set of business rules is used to calculate this element.   A count is generated from the number of sources updated in the last 24 months for some of the person-level data, and then that count is  transformed into values of 01-10.
Value Encodings: 00 = Match No Record Content|01 = Smallest Marketing Footprint|02|03|04|05|06|07|08|09|10 = Largest Marketing Footprint
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules review the person-scoped elements and their contributing sources to provide this indicator.

Value Encodings: 00 = Match No Record Content|01 = Smallest Marketing Footprint|02|03|04|05|06|07|08|09|10 = Largest Marketing Footprint
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules review the household-scoped elements and their contributing sources to provide this indicator.

Description:
Indicates the Year and Month of Birth associated with the person.  The DAY of birth is not included.
An estimated 3% of matched records will only contain year of birth data.
  This DOB element contains no DAY of birth, but the length of the element is 8 positions (YYYYMM00). Whenever there is a Year and a Month present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year of birth and no month of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|00 fields.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Attribute Name: Date of Birth - Person Default to 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM)
Description:
Indicates the year and month of birth associated with the person, defaulting to the 1st ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
If the year and month of birth for the individual appearing on your customer file is not available, the year and month of birth for the 1st person will be appended. 
To distinguish between the year and month of birth appended for the person and the 1st ranked person in the household, a precision indicator is also appended.    The day of birth is not included.

An estimated 3% of matched records will only contain year of birth data.

   This element contains no DAY of birth, but the length of the element is 8 positions (YYYYMM00).  The day portion of the element will be set to 00.

  When there is no year of birth and no month of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM00 fields.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Attribute Name: Date of Birth - 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM/DD)
Description:
Indicates the Year, Month and Day of Birth associated with the 1st ranked person in the household.  The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Acxiom policy allows full DOB to be provided to clients for legitimate reference purposes and applications. Description: This model uses element #7795 Stocks/Bonds and applies household inferred data on top of it.  The value of 01 is the same counts as 7795 Stocks/Bonds. The inferred modeled portion, values 2-9, uses syndicated survey data for the target variable.  The element outputs a relative rank indicating the likelihood of the household being interested in investments.  A value of '01' means most likely to be an Investor and '09' least likely. A value of blank means there is no information available about the household.
Value Encodings: 1 = Stocks and Bonds|2 = Top group of modeled investors|3 = Second group of modeled investors|4 = Third group of modeled investors|5 = Fourth group of modeled investors|6 = Fifth group of modeled investors|7 = Sixth group of modeled investors|8 = Seventh group of modeled investors|9 = Bottom group of modeled investors
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported data and Acxiom modeled data

Sub-Category-Lev2: People in the HH - HH Size
Description: Indicates the known number of known people in the household, both adults and children.  Household Size is a sum of Number of Adults and Number of Children, with the exception of a small percentage of Household Size (0.04%) that will not sum to Number of Adults + Number of Children.
Value Encodings: 1 = 1 Person in the Household|2 = 2 People in the Household|3 = 3 People in the Household|4 = 4 People in the Household|5 = 5 People in the Household|6 = 6 People in the Household|7 = 7 People in the Household|8 = 8 People in the Household|9 = Greater than 8 People in the Household
Source/Point of Collection: This element is inferred from the adults that have been householded together plus the value in number of children.

Attribute Name: Adult Age Ranges Present - 55 to 64 Unknown Gender - 100%
Description: Indicates the presence of people of unknown gender aged 55 to 64 in the household. Based on 9600 Adult Age Ranges, data calculated from the mode of the ZIP9 or ZIP is added to the unknown gender age ranges in this element to reach 100% match rate of the whole element.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported data, Acxiom modeled data, ZIP+4, and ZIP data

Sub-Category-Lev2: People in the HH - HH Size
Description:
Indicates the number of known people in the household, both adults and children.   This element includes 1) 8629 Household Size and 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring household size coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended.  
1) For the 8629 Household Size portion, it is a sum of Number of Adults and Number of Children. 
2) For the inference rule portion, since the household size coverage percentage for 2 people in the household is lower than census, the rule only infers the value of 2 people in the household.

(Note:  There is a small percentage of Household Size (0.005%) that will not sum to Number of Adults + Number of Children.)

Description:
Indicates whether anyone in the household is married.  This element includes 1) 9609 Marital Status in the Household and 2) business rule inferences that create Inferred Married and Inferred Single to increase marital status coverage. 
1) For the 8609 Marital Status portion, it is fed by consumer self-reported marital data.
2) Inferred Married and Inferred Single, values A and B, are inferred based on business rules.  Inferred Married - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there are 2 names in the household with gender of Male and Female, within a certain age range of each other, then marital status is set to A "Inferred Married".  Inferred Single - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there is only one name in the household, then the marital status is set to B "Inferred Single".
Value Encodings: M = Married|S = Single|A = Inferred Married|B = Inferred Single
Source/Point of Collection: The Married and Single values are consumer self-reported.  The Inferred Married and Inferred Single values are inferred from the people and the ages that exist in the household.

Attribute Name: Geoscape - African American Educational Attainment Index
Description: The Educational Attainment Indices is a percentile ranking of block groups using a 0 to 100 scale. It is based on overall level of educational attainment for persons aged 25 and above. This is a percentile ranking of neighborhoods based on their overall number of years of education completed. A higher score represents the most years of education completed.
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Description: Socioeconomic Status (SES) is a blend of income, education, occupation and housing characteristics. SES helps identify consumer purchasing power and preferences. Households are grouped into common segments as an A-E index by block group. "A" is the highest level of socioeconomic status while "E" is the lowest level. SES A: Households with over $85,000 annual household income, 4 year college degree or graduate degree, owned housing, and employed in professional occupations. SES B: Households generally between $50,000 and $120,000 annual household income, some college or higher education, owned housing, professional or skilled occupation. SES C: Households usually between $30,000 and $75,000 annual household income, high school graduate to some college, and employed as skilled labor or service worker. SES D: Households typically between $15,000 and $35,000 annual household income, high school or lower education, rented housing, employed as service or labor worker. SES E: Households most often below $20,000 annual household income; less than high school education; rented housing, labor or service worker or unemployed. Note: Tract and ZIP Code values are based on the block groups located within these larger geographies.
Value Encodings: A = Highest Level of Socioeconomic Status|B = Medium-High Level of Socioeconomic Status|C = Medium Level of Socioeconomic Status|D = Medium-Low Level of Socioeconomic Status|E = Lowest Level of Socioeconomic Status
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Description: The level of Spanish language usage within the Hispanic population and households (age 5+). A blend of several household and population language usage indicators are factored into 5 English-Spanish language segments. The Hispanic Language Usage Segment indicates the overall language preference (English versus Spanish) for Hispanic households and population. Block groups, census tracts, and ZIP Codes are assigned one of the five codes based on language preference. HL1: English Dependent HL2: Bi-Lingual English Preferred HL3: Bi-Lingual English & Spanish Equally Used HL4: Bi-Lingual Spanish Preferred HL5: Spanish Dependent
Value Encodings: HL1 = English Dependent|HL2 = Bi-Lingual English Preferred|HL3 = Bi-Lingual English and Spanish Equally Used|HL4 = Bi-Lingual Spanish Preferred|HL5 = Spanish Dependent

Description: A blended indicator of ethnicity, immigration and language factored into a qualitative representation of the level of acculturation. Classifies block groups into five assimilation segments based on the Hispanicity Index, which is a blend of ethnicity, immigration and language factors. Values range from "HA1" (very acculturated) to "HA5" (unacculturated). The following describes the typical Hispanic for each segment. HA1: Americanizado. English dominant (nearly no Spanish); born in US and often 3rd+ generation; has few Hispanic cultural practices. HA2: Nueva Latina. English preferred (some Spanish); born in U.S. and typically 2nd generation; some Hispanic cultural practices and often retro-acculturate. HA3: Bi-Cultural Hispanic. Bilingual (equal or nearly); immigrated as child or young adult; has many Hispanic cultural practices. HA4: Hispano. Spanish preferred (some English); immigrated as adult and in U.S. 10+ years; pre-dominant Hispanic cultural practices. HA5: Latinoamericana. Spanish dominant (nearly no English); recent immigrant as adult (less than 10 years ago); primarily Hispanic cultural practices and identifies with home country more so than U.S. Hispanic.
Value Encodings: HA1 = Americanizado: English dominant (nearly no Spanish); born in U.S., third+ generation; few Hispanic cultural practices|HA2 = Nueva Latina: English preferred (some Spanish); born in U.S., second generation; some Hispanic cultural practices; often retro-acculturate|HA3 = Bi-Cultural Hispanic: Bi-Lingual (equal or nearly); immigrant as a child or young adult; many Hispanic cultural practices|HA4 = Hispano: Spanish preferred (some English); immigrant as adult, and in U.S. 10+ years; predominant Hispanic cultural practices|HA5 = Latinoamericana: Spanish dominant (nearly no English); recent immigrant as adult, less than 10 years ago; primarily Hispanic cultural practices; identifies with home country more than U.S.
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Description: A blended indicator of ethnicity, immigration and language factored into a percentile ranking of block group areas. The direction of this variable, "1" is most acculturated and "100" is least acculturated, allows for direct comparison to language and foreign born indices. The values are from 1-100; not applicable is indicated by a "0". Tract and ZIP Code values are based on the block groups located within these larger geographies.
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Description: The Educational Attainment Indices is a percentile ranking of block groups using a 0 to 100 scale. It is based on overall level of educational attainment for persons aged 25 and above. This is a percentile ranking of neighborhoods based on their overall number of years of education completed. A higher score represents the most years of education completed.

Description: Socioeconomic Status (SES) is a blend of income, education, occupation and housing characteristics. SES helps identify consumer purchasing power and preferences. Households are grouped into common segments as an A-E index by block group. "A" is the highest level of socioeconomic status while "E" is the lowest level. SES A: Households with over $85,000 annual household income, 4 year college degree or graduate degree, owned housing, and employed in professional occupations. SES B: Households generally between $50,000 and $120,000 annual household income, some college or higher education, owned housing, professional or skilled occupation. SES C: Households usually between $30,000 and $75,000 annual household income, high school graduate to some college, and employed as skilled labor or service worker. SES D: Households typically between $15,000 and $35,000 annual household income, high school or lower education, rented housing, employed as service or labor worker. SES E: Households most often below $20,000 annual household income; less than high school education; rented housing, labor or service worker or unemployed. Note: Tract and ZIP Code values are based on the block groups located within these larger geographies.
Value Encodings: A = Highest Level of Socioeconomic Status|B = Medium-High Level of Socioeconomic Status|C = Medium Level of Socioeconomic Status|D = Medium-Low Level of Socioeconomic Status|E = Lowest Level of Socioeconomic Status
Source/Point of Collection: This partner data is provided from Geoscape.  Geoscape provides a set of software, libraries and tables for Acxiom to install.  Currently this data is applied at the block group level, but we will be moving several of the data to the individual level later this year.

Attribute Name: Credit Card Indicator - Gas Department Retail
Description: Indicates possession of gas, department store, or retail store credit card(s) in a household. A department store card is like JCPenney, Sears, or Montgomery Ward. A retail card is like Home Depot, Victoria Secret, or Best Buy.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported and summarized purchase data. The consumer self-reported data is generally provided based on a consumer indicating that these credit card types exist in the household.

Attribute Name: Credit Card Indicator - Travel and Entertainment
Description: Indicates possession of travel and entertainment credit card(s) in a household. Travel and entertainment cards are generally used to pay for hotel, airline, and other business related expenses. Diners Club and American Express are the most well known T&E cards. Many banks have specific T&E cards in addition to their other cards (i.e., CapitalOne Venture, Citi AAdvantage World). A few of the airlines also offer T&E cards (i.e., Delta Airlines Skymiles, Southwest Rapid Rewards).
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported and summarized purchase data. The consumer self-reported data is generally provided based on a consumer indicating that these credit card types exist in the household.

Description: The input individual has been identified as having living relative, believed to be their parent, who (Parent) is age 60+ and has a net worth of $250k+.
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules examine current and historical households to determine the family connections.  The data indicates there is a family connection found, but the family members are not indicated or named for consumer protection.

Attribute Name: Family Ties - Parent 1 Income - Estimated Household - Higher Ranges - Person
Description: The Income range of an older relative (Parent1) of the person on the client record.
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules examine current and historical households to determine the family connections.  The data indicates there is a family connection found, but the family members are not indicated or named for consumer protection.

Attribute Name: Family Ties - Parent 1 Net Worth - Person
Description: The Net Worth Gold of an older relative (Parent1) of the person on the client record. The basis for the model was the Federal Reserves Survey of Consumer Finance (SCF). Demographic data on the SCF survey was mapped into the same format as InfoBase data and used to build a prediction of Net Worth. Some area level data was also used in the model, primarily when specific household elements were unavailable.
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules examine current and historical households to determine the family connections.  The data indicates there is a family connection found, but the family members are not indicated or named for consumer protection.

Description: Indicates the estimated available equity for a mortgage.
Source/Point of Collection: Real property data and consumer self-reported data.

Attribute Name: Home Equity Available - Estimated - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the home equity available for the mortgage in ranges.
Source/Point of Collection:
Equity in a property is estimated as part of the Loan Model process. Once the active loans are known, each are amortized forward from their loan dates and the total remaining balance is estimated across all of the loans. This does not consider extra payments, late payments, late fees, etc., which would only be known to the lender and the borrower. 
Comparing the home market value to the estimated remaining balance, the equity for a specific property can be estimated.

Attribute Name: Home Equity Lendable - Estimated - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Lendable equity is computed on 80% of market value less total loans. It is derived from public record sources.
Source/Point of Collection:

Attribute Name: Home Owners Insurance Expiration Date (Real Property data only) - Loan Month

Attribute Name: Home Owners Insurance Expiration Date (Real Property data only) - Purchase Date

Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Attribute Name: Home Loan Amount Total - Original - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the total home loan amount for the household in ranges. There may be multiple loans on the home.
Source/Point of Collection: The loan data is based on public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices, property loan history, and loan status for properties where loan transactions are available.  Loan position indicates the order in which lenders get paid in the event of a default. Thus, a first position loan is paid first, followed by a second position loan, and so on. Typically, the largest loan on a property is in first position, but there are scenarios where this may not be the case. Sometimes the public record from the County Recorder will indicate loan position, but this is not always true, which is why additional logic in the Loan Model must be applied to estimate the position.

Attribute Name: Home Line of Credit 2 (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates that the Home Loan Amount 2 (element 8568 & element 8747) is an open line of credit (HELOC). An open line of credit doesnt necessarily mean the property owner has borrowed the entire amount. It simply means that they have an open line of credit up to that amount.
Value Encodings: Y = Line is Open Line of Credit
Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Attribute Name: Home Loan-to-Value - Estimated - Actual (Real Property data only)
Description: Loan-to-value (LTV) ratio expresses the amount of total loans (current and historical) as a percentage of home market value. Note that InfoBase does not 'pay down' loans. It is derived from public record sources (county recorder and assessor offices).
Source/Point of Collection: A calculation between the home's market value and the loan amount.

Description: Indicates that someone in the household owns a life insurance policy.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported.

Description:
Indicates the estimated household income in higher ranges and narrower ranges.
This income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
The match rate and distribution for this element will not match the other income elements, because the sources that feed 8201 are slightly different.  The agreement between them will be about 85-90%.
Source/Point of Collection: This income element is based on income values provided by several sources, each of which models income with their own proprietary model.  There is a bit of self-reported data in it, but it is less than 5%. Rules are used to examine all the source data to output the best income value from amongst them.

Description:
Indicates the estimated household income in broad ranges. 
This income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
This income element also has two other versions, 1) 9641 Income Plus which uses inferred data to fill-in the missing data in this income up to the household level match rate. And 2) 7641 which uses the mode of the ZIP9 to fill in the missing data in 9641 Plus Income up to 100%.
Source/Point of Collection: This income element is based on income values provided by several sources, each of which models income with their own proprietary model.  There is a bit of self-reported data in it, but it is less than 5%. Rules are used to examine all the source data to output the best income value from amongst them.

Description:
Indicates the estimated household income in broad ranges.
This income uses 8641 Income as it's foundation.  9641 Income Plus fills in the missing data in 8641 Income with inferred income, up to the household level match rate, generally 88%-93%, but it depends on the client file.
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
Description of 8641 Income: 8641 Income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.
Source/Point of Collection: This income element containes the best income value chosen from the modeled income values provided from the sources, and Acxiom modeled data.

Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.

Attribute Name: Economic Assessment - ITA Index - Zip+4 Aggregate
Description: Indicates financial risk. The highest financial risk is at the low end of the scale and the lowest financial risk is at the top. It is a raw index range of 001 - 200 used primarily for analytical purposes.
Source/Point of Collection: This data is calculated from aggregated credit data variables.   At least 7 households are required to be in the area to be aggregated. If there are not at least 7 households in a ZIP+4, ZIP+4s with households that have similar levels of total credit balance for the last 12 months, and which are in the same Census Block Group are combined to reach the 7-household threshold. Cnce the data is built at the combined level, it is propagated to ZIP4s, which is the geographic level at which the data is matched and appended.
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Attribute Name: Economic Assessment - ITA Index - Zip+4 Aggregate - Precision Level
Description: Indicates the precision of the data appended: ZIP+4
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Attribute Name: Economic Assessment - ITA Score - Zip+4 Aggregate
Description: Indicates financial risk. The raw index scores are converted to industry-like financial scores of 450 - 850.
Source/Point of Collection: This data is calculated from aggregated credit data variables.   At least 7 households are required to be in the area to be aggregated. If there are not at least 7 households in a ZIP+4, ZIP+4s with households that have similar levels of total credit balance for the last 12 months, and which are in the same Census Block Group are combined to reach the 7-household threshold. Cnce the data is built at the combined level, it is propagated to ZIP4s, which is the geographic level at which the data is matched and appended.
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Attribute Name: Economic Assessment - ITA Score - Zip+4 Aggregate - Precision Level
Description: Indicates the precision of the data appended: ZIP+4
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Description: Identifies areas of either low or high concentration of open auto loans. The values are used to create an average and then each Zip+4 is assigned an index which indicates a higher or lower than average Zip+4.
Value Encodings: L = Areas with lower concentration of open auto loans|H = Areas with higher concentration of open auto loans
Source/Point of Collection: This data is calculated from aggregated credit data variables.   At least 7 households are required to be in the area to be aggregated. If there are not at least 7 households in a ZIP+4, ZIP+4s with households that have similar levels of total credit balance for the last 12 months, and which are in the same Census Block Group are combined to reach the 7-household threshold. Cnce the data is built at the combined level, it is propagated to ZIP4s, which is the geographic level at which the data is matched and appended.
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Description: Resource based index of household spending capacity rather than strictly a measure of available assets. Created by comparing earnings and equity to debt, and looking at length of residence, age, presence of children, local tax rates, invested assets, home equity loans, projected savings, and indicators of cash flow and spending behavior.
Model reflects housing costs, cost of living, tax rates and other factors and covers income up to $2MM per household.
Modeled home market value.
Modeled income data. There are 13 income ranges from under $30K - $500K+.
Identifies best prospective donors and provides insight on the relative amount they are likely to give. Donors scoring in the top decile of the index donated 77% more than the average gift amount.

The Life Insurance Targeting Index was derived from over nine years of anonymous survey data collected by the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System. This survey research data was used in combination with know life insurance holders and other demographic and behavioral data elements to create an index and score of all the households in the U.S. for the likelihood to purchase a whole life or term life policy.

If there are not at least 7 households in a ZIP+4, ZIP+4s with households that have similar levels of total credit balance for the last 12 months, and which are in the same Census Block Group are combined to reach the 7-household threshold. Since the data is built at the combined level, it is propagated to ZIP4s, which is the geographic level at which the data is matched and appended.
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

If there are not at least 7 households in a ZIP+4, ZIP+4s with households that have similar levels of total credit balance for the last 12 months, and which are in the same Census Block Group are combined to reach the 7-household threshold. Since the data is built at the combined level, it is propagated to ZIP4s, which is the geographic level at which the data is matched and appended.
Restrictions: R3 - Restricted Client List. PIA Required.

Description: IPA segments the U.S. affluence and wealth markets through incorporating all incoming producing assets a household is projected to have, beyond net worth and gross assets. IPA recognizes that as Americans get wealthier, their assets holdings change, and takes this growth curve into account. Households are assigned to one of eleven segments, ranked from lowest estimated assets (01) to highest (11).

Description: PRIZM Premier classifies U.S. households into one of 68 consumer segments based on the households likely purchasing preferences. This segmentation system incorporates both income producing assets and technology adoption into the PRIZM geodemographic framework. The 68 segments are numbered according to socioeconomic rank (which takes into account characteristics such as income, education, occupation and home value).

Description: Neighborhood Factors is a geographically-based attribute that summarily represents factors of a neighborhood in which a person resides that could contribute to behaviors in the marketplace. Consumers are assigned to one of ten segments based on the characteristics of their neighborhood, such as number of grocery stores and hospitals, height of FCC towers, environmental risks like earthquakes and wildfires, and weather conditions.
Value Encodings: 01 = Towers & Tropics|02 = Airlines & Apartments|03 = Stacked High-Risers|04 = Clear Diversity|05 = Southern Sol|06 = Melting Pots|07 = Alternate Transportation|08 = Close Quarters|09 = Power Players|10 = Focused & Frugal

Description: The Cost of Living Composite Index measures relative price levels for consumer goods and services in participating areas (the composite of the other indices). The average for all participating places, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each participants index is read as a percentage of the average for all places.

The Cost of Living Grocery Index measures relative price levels for groceries at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.

The Cost of Living Healthcare Index measures relative healthcare costs at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.

The Cost of Living Housing Index measures relative housing costs at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.

The Cost of Living Miscellaneous Index measures relative miscellaneous costs (not included at the other indices) at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.

The Cost of Living Transportation Index measures relative transportation costs at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.

The Cost of Living Utility Index measures relative utility costs at the county level. The average for all counties, both metropolitan and nonmetropolitan, equals 100, and each countys index is read as a comparison to that average, either higher or lower.
Total number of people (population count for Block Group, Tract or ZIP, depending on level of append).

Attribute Name: Number of People in Households (Household Population)
Description: Total number of people living in households (household population count for the Tract if appended at the Block Group or Tract levels, and for the ZIP if appended at that level).

Attribute Name: Number of People in Group Quarters (Group-Quarters Population)
Description: Total number of people living in group quarters (group quarters population count for Tract if appended at the Block Group or Tract levels, and for the ZIP if appended at that level). Note: The Census Bureau classifies all people not living in households as living in group quarters.
Total number of households. Note: This includes family and non-family (unrelated people living together) households.

Total number of families (family households). Note: A family consists of 2 or more people living together with one person related to the householder by birth, marriage or adoption. Note: In the Census, the householder of a household is designated by the person who fills out the form. In most cases, this is the person, or one of the people, in whose name the home is owned, being bought, or rented. If there is no such person in the household, any household member 15 years old or over could be designated as the householder.

Attribute Name: Renter-occupied Housing Units - Average Gross Rent (in $US)
Description: The average gross rent for renter-occupied housing units. Note: "Gross rent" is the contract rent plus the estimated average monthly cost of utilities (electricity, gas, water and sewer) and fuels (oil, coal, kerosene, wood, etc.) if these are paid by the renter (or paid for the renter by someone else). Gross rent is intended to eliminate differentials that result from varying practices with respect to the inclusion of utilities and fuels as part of the rental payment.

Attribute Name: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - First Name
Description: Indicates the first name of the 1st ranked person  in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  This element includes 3 fields, Name 8610_01, Middle Initial 8610_02 and Gender 8610_03.
Source/Point of Collection: Self-reported, purchase transactions, and public data contribute to name.  To get gender, that name is then matched against a name/gender table first and if a name is not on the table, source data (which may be from a name/gender table or consumer self-reported) is used to assign a gender.
Restrictions: R3 - No placement on digital platforms, i.e., AC, KinessoAudiences, Adobe, The Trade Desk

Attribute Name: Family Ties - Parent 1 State Code - Person
Description: The state of residence code of an older relative (Parent1) of the person on the client record.
Value Encodings: The values in this element are the state abbreviations. (i.e., AK, AL, AR, AZ, CA, CO, CT, DC, DE, FL, etc.)
Source/Point of Collection: Business rules examine current and historical households to determine the family connections.  The data indicates there is a family connection found, but the family members are not indicated or named for consumer protection.

Attribute Name: Fips County Code (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the 3-digit Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) code that uniquely identifies each county within a state. County boundaries are shown on most census maps. Counties are numbered in alphabetical sequence, with independent cities numbered separately at the end of the list.
Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Description: Identifies the 435 geographic areas within the United States served by a member of the U.S. House of Representatives. After the apportionment of congressional seats among the states, based on census population counts, each state is responsible for establishing Congressional Districts (CDs) for the purpose of electing representatives. Each CD is to be as equal in population to all other CDs in the state as practicable. The District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the Island Areas have code 98 assigned identifying their nonvoting delegate status with respect to representation in Congress. CDs are typically built from Census blocks. Use with State FIPS code for unique identifier.

Attribute Name: Geo State Upper House District Code
Description: State Legislative Districts (SLDs) are the areas from which members are elected to state legislatures. The upper house (SLDU), the Senate, is one of the two chambers of the U.S. bicameral legislature, the other chamber being the lower house (SLDL). Nebraska has a unicameral legislature and the District of Columbia has a single council, both of which the Census Bureau treats as upper-chamber legislative areas for the purpose of data presentation. A unique identifier, selected by state participants, is assigned to each SLDU within a state. In Connecticut, Hawaii, Illinois, Louisiana, Maine, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Ohio, and Puerto Rico, state officials did not define the SLDUs to cover all of the state or state equivalent area (usually bodies of water). In these areas with no SLDUs defined, the code "ZZZ" has been assigned, which is treated within state as a single SLDU for purposes of data presentation. Maryland also has areas with no SLDUs defined; in Maryland, these areas are coded with an initial "Z" by county or equivalent and treated as a unique SLD by county or equivalent.

A time zone is a region that observes a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes. The time-zone code is an alpha-numeric representation of the 7 time zones pertaining to the 50 states and D.C. From East to West: Atlantic Time Zone; Eastern Time Zone; Central Time Zone; Mountain Time Zone; Pacific Time Zone; Alaskan Time Zone; Hawaiian-Aleutian Time Zone.
Value Encodings: A = Alaskan|C = Central|E = Eastern|H = Hawaiian-Aleutian|M = Mountain|P = Pacific|T = Atlantic

Description: A time zone is a region that observes a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes. The time zone name is the formal name that corresponds with the time zone code.
The number of time-zones a location is away from the Greenwich meridian - one hour for each time zone. This is also known as Greenwich Mean Time. Values are -11:00 to 12:00.
Indicates whether the region in which the address is located observes the practice of advancing standard time by one hour in the spring of each year and reverting to standard time in the fall.

A four-digit numeric code that, when used with the FIPS State and County codes and the Census Tract code, provides a unique identifier for each Census Block. A Census Block is subdivision of a census tract and the smallest geographic unit for which the Census Bureau tabulates its data.

The first digit of the Census block code that, when used with the FIPS State and County codes and the Census Tract code, provides a unique identifier for each Census block group. A Census block group is a subdivision of a census tract and refers to an area that contains an average of 500 households.

Attribute Name: Geo Core Based Statistical Area (CBSA) Code
Description: Core Based Statistical Areas (CBSAs) may be either Metropolitan Statistical Areas or Micropolitan Statistical Areas. Metropolitan Statistical Areas consist of at least one urbanized area of 50,000 or more population plus adjacent territory that has a high degree of social and economic integration with the core as measured by commuting ties. Micropolitan Statistical Areas a new set of statistical areas consist of at least one urban cluster of at least 10,000 but less than 50,000 population plus adjacent territory that has a high degree of social and economic integration with the core as measured by commuting ties. Metropolitan and Micropolitan Statistical Areas are defined in terms of whole counties (or equivalent entities).

The geographic areas in the United States in which local television viewing is measured by The Nielsen Company. A DMA region is a group of counties that form an exclusive geographic area in which the home market television stations hold a dominance of total hours viewed. There are 210 DMA regions, covering the entire continental United States, Hawaii, and parts of Alaska. The DMA boundaries and DMA data are owned solely and exclusively by The Nielsen Company. Any use and or reproduction of these materials without the express written consent of The Nielsen Company is strictly prohibited.

A unique identifier for each Minor Civil Division (MCD) or other county subdivisions in the U.S. MCDs are legal entities that are subdivisions of county or county equivalents other than incorporated places and are established by appropriate state or local governmental authorities and recognized by the Census Bureau as a primary county division; for example, a township in Ohio, a town in Vermont, a magisterial district in Virginia. The Census Bureau recognizes MCDs in 28 States, Puerto Rico, and in all the Outlying and freely associated areas. Other county subdivisions represented by this code include Census County Divisions (CCDs), Census Subareas, unorganized territories, and incorporated places that are independent of any MCD.

Other county subdivisions represented by this code include Census County Divisions (CCDs), Census Subareas, unorganized territories, and incorporated places that are independent of any MCD.

Provides county size definitions, ranking areas by the 2010 Census Household Counts. The ranked list is divided so that A counties account for 40%, B counties account for 30% and C and D counties each account for 15% of the U.S. Total Households. The areas ranked are metropolitan areas or individual non-metropolitan counties. A = A county belonging to one of the 21 largest metropolitan areas based on household counts from the 2010 Census; B = All counties not included under A that are in metropolitan areas with more than 85,000 households according to the 2010 census; C = All counties not included under A or B that either have more than 20,000 households or are in metropolitan areas with more than 20,000 households according to the 2010 census; D = All remaining counties; 0 = Outside of the 50 states and D.C..

A unique identifier for each legally bounded concentration of population or other bounded area identified by the Census Bureau as a Census Designated Place (CDP). An incorporated place will be legally described as a borough (except in Alaska and New York), a city, a town (except in New England, New York, and Wisconsin), or a village.

Specifies the reference point used to append the geocodes to each record. Most of the time, the geocodes are for the exact or approximate location of the address that has been input into the system. When an address-point is not available, the system uses the next most granular reference point that can be located for the address and appends the geocodes for that point; first the ZIP+4 centroid (center-point), then the ZIP+2 centroid, and finally the ZIP centroid.
Value Encodings: A = Address Point|1 = Street Segment|2 = ZIP+4 Centroid|3 = Intersection/Street|4 = ZIP+2 Centroid|5 = ZIP Centroid

A 6-byte code made up of a 4-byte prefix and a 2-byte suffix. When used with the FIPS State and County codes, it provides a unique identifier for each Census tract. Census tracts are the basic county subdivision used by the Census Bureau for census collection and dissemination purposes and contain an average of 1,500 households.

An eight-digit number along with a decimal point and a plus or minus sign (+/-) representing the angular distance north or south from a point on the earth's surface to the equator, measured on the meridian of the point. Positions 1-2 represent degrees and are separated by a decimal point from the rightmost 6 positions that represent a portion of a degree (minutes and seconds). Positive latitude values indicate the Northern Hemisphere while negative latitude values indicate the Southern Hemisphere.

A nine-digit number along with a decimal point and a plus or minus sign (+/-) representing the angular distance east or west from a point on the earths surface to the prime meridian at Greenwich, England, measured on the meridian of the point. Positions 1-3 represent a degree and are separated by a decimal point from the rightmost 6 positions that represent a portion of a degree (minutes and seconds). Positive longitude values indicate the Eastern Hemisphere while negative latitude values indicate the Western Hemisphere.

Attribute Name: Home Market Value - Estimated - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the market value of the home in ranges. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source. Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data. Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.  8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value
Source/Point of Collection: The Real Property source models this data based on public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices, and from a nationwide residential property and sale database.  Market value estimates rely on highly localized and recent sales transaction data, therefore capturing the micro-location deviations in the local real estate market.

Attribute Name: Home Assessed Value - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the assessed value of the home, in ranges. The assessed value is the amount, stated in a ranged array, at which the home was last assessed by the local government. Current assessed value, by range, of property (land & improvements) for taxation as determined by the county assessor. An assessed value is the dollar value assigned to a property for purposes of measuring applicable taxes. Assessed valuation is used to determine the value of a residence for tax purposes and takes home market value into consideration.     County assessments are done periodically, i.e., every 5 years, unless in the cases of an improvement to the property, such as building a home on the property, a home remodel, etc. which would cause a new assessment at that time.    This assessed value comes straight from the county offices, not manipulated by the source or Acxiom.
Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Source/Point of Collection: The Real Property source models this data based on public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices, and from a nationwide residential property and sale database.  Market value estimates rely on highly localized and recent sales transaction data, therefore capturing the micro-location deviations in the local real estate market.

Attribute Name: Home Assessed Value - Actual (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the assessed value of the home. An assessed value is the dollar value assigned to a property for purposes of measuring applicable taxes. Assessed valuation is used to determine the value of a residence for tax purposes and takes home market value into consideration. County assessments are done periodically, i.e., every 5 years, unless in the cases of an improvement to the property, such as building a home on the property, a home remodel, etc. which would cause a new assessment at that time. This assessed value comes straight from the county offices, not manipulated by the source or Acxiom.
Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Attribute Name: Home Market Value - Estimated - Quality Indicator (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the method used to derive the home market value estimate. This element works in conjunction with the following single-sourced real property elements:  9750 Home Market Value - Actual  8583 Home Market Value - Premier Ranges  8438 Home Market Value - Ranges
Value Encodings: 1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.|2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV|4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV|5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value
Source/Point of Collection: The Real Property source models this data based on public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices, and from a nationwide residential property and sale database.  Market value estimates rely on highly localized and recent sales transaction data, therefore capturing the micro-location deviations in the local real estate market.

Attribute Name: Home Market Value - Estimated - Actual (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the actual (not a range) market value of the home. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source.    Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data.   Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.    8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value
Source/Point of Collection: The Real Property source models this data based on public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices, and from a nationwide residential property and sale database.  Market value estimates rely on highly localized and recent sales transaction data, therefore capturing the micro-location deviations in the local real estate market.

Attribute Name: Home Loan-to-Value - Estimated - Ranges (Real Property data only)
Description: Loan-to-value (LTV) ratio expresses the amount of total loans (current and historical) as a percentage of home market value. Note that InfoBase does not 'pay down' loans. It is derived from public record sources (county recorder and assessor offices).
Source/Point of Collection: A calculation between the home's market value and the loan amount.

Attribute Name: Home Owner Type Detail (Real Property data only)
Description: Indicates the specific type of homeowner: Company Owner - The property is owned by a company and not owner-occupied. These records are not read into our mart build, so there is not any coverage for this value. Residential Owner - Homestead Flag - If a Homestead/Home Owner exemption flag is present, then the owner occupancy is inferred from this data. The exemption (or discount in property taxes) can only be taken if that property is the primary residence and occupied by the owner. It is also known as the Home Owner Exemption. This is a tax break for people who reside in their home vs. renting it out to someone else. Investor / Individual Owner - The property is owned by an investor and not owner occupied. These records are not read into our mart build, so there is not any coverage for this value. Residential Owner - Mail / Site Address - Owner-occupied and the mailing and site address are the same. Inferred Owner Occupied - Records that could not be coded as an H or O. We used the AbiliTec address links and if the mail link and address link were the same, then we inferred as owner-occupied.
Value Encodings: C = Company Owner|H = Residential Owner - Homestead Flag|I = Investor / Individual Owner|O = Residential Owner - Mail / Site Address|E = Inferred Owner Occupied
Source/Point of Collection: Public real property data from assessor and recorder county offices.

Description: Indicates if more than one family lives at a particular address. Single-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing one family or household, such as a house. The building does not share an inside wall with any other house or dwelling. It does not touch any other dwelling. Multi-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing more than one household. i.e., Multiple separate housing units for residential inhabitants are contained within one building or several buildings within one complex, such as an apartment building. Condos are coded as multi-family dwelling units.
Value Encodings: M = Multiple Family Dwelling Unit|S = Single Family Dwelling Unit

Attribute Name: Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 1 - Date
Description: Indicates the category of recent retail purchase activity. There are 5 of these elements:  Element: 9156 Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 1   Element: 9157 Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 2   Element: 9158 Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 3   Element: 9159 Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 4   Element: 9160 Retail Purchase Activity Date and Category 5   They are sorted by most recent date to least recent date; then within date sorted by category descending.   If there are more than 5, only the most recent 5 are kept.  They could all have the same date, but be different categories.  They could all have different dates, but be the same category.   They could all have different dates and different categories.

Description: This element is created from the number of different catalog merchants from which the individual has made purchases. This element can be used with 8658 RFM Catalog Buyer Recency - Input Individual, which indicates the time-frame in which the catalog purchases have been made.
Value Encodings: A = Purchased from a Catalog 1 time|B = Purchased from a Catalog 2 - 3 times|C = Purchased from a Catalog 4 - 5 times|D = Purchased from a Catalog 6 - 10 times|E = Purchased from a Catalog more than 10 times
Source/Point of Collection: Summarized purchase transactions

Description: This element is created from the last time an individual has made a purchase from a catalog merchant. This element can be used with 8657 RFM Catalog Buyer Frequency - Input Individual, which indicates the number of times the individual has made a purchase from different catalog merchants.
Value Encodings: A = Catalog Buyer within 6 months|B = Catalog Buyer within 7 - 12 Months|C = Catalog Buyer within 13 - 18 Months|D = Catalog Buyer within 19 - 24 Months|E = Catalog Buyer greater than 24 Months
Source/Point of Collection: Summarized purchase transactions

Description: Indicates the total number of vehicles owned in the household.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported.  Number of vehicles is inferred by counting the number of vehicles that have been reported.

Description: Indicates that someone in the household is a classic car owner. This includes any vehicle that is older than 20 years. The valid value is the model year of the vehicle. This could be a motorcycle, truck, or a car. Acxioms vehicle data does not fall under the DPPA (Drivers Privacy Protection Act). The DPPA prohibits the release or use of personal information about an individual in connection with a motor vehicle record. Acxioms vehicle data is not sourced from motor vehicle records. It is sourced from surveys, completed by consumers, which were sent due to a vehicle warranty purchase, vehicle service/repair or from a product registration.
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported

Description: Indicates the code of the make of the 1st vehicle in the household. Vehicles are householded using Last Name and Address Link. Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported.  Business rules compare the make and model of the vehicle to a table to infer the type.

Description: This element indicates the type of vehicle that exists in Vehicle 2 (elements 9050-9054). It can be used to determine the household's vehicle 'lifestyle'. If the client needs to know when the vehicle was last known to be owned by the household, use 9057 Vehicle Verification Date 2.
Value Encodings: C1 = Entry Compact Car|C4 = Premium Compact Car|F4 = Premium Full-size Car|L1 = Entry Luxury Car|L2 = Mid-Size Luxury Car|L3 = Sports Luxury Car|L4 = Premium Luxury Car|M1 = Entry Mid-size Car|M4 = Premium Mid-size Car|P1 = Compact Pickup|P2 = Light Duty Full-size Pickup|P3 = Heavy Duty Full-size Pickup|P4 = Luxury Full-size Pickup|S1 = Entry Sports Car|S4 = Premium Sports Car|U1 = Compact SUV|U2 = Mid-size SUV|U3 = Full-size SUV|U4 = Luxury SUV|V1 = Compact Van|V3 = Full-size Van
Source/Point of Collection: Consumer self-reported.  Business rules compare the make and model of the vehicle to a table to infer the type.
